Descriptive analysis

  1. Dataset size: ~101,766 hospital encounters large, reliable for analysis
  2. Encounter vs patient IDs: Multiple encounters per patient readmission analyzed at visit level
  3. Length of stay: Mean 4.6 days; skewed distribution (max = 14) subset of complex hospitalizations
  4. Lab procedures: Mean 34 indicates high clinical intensity and monitoring
  5. Number of procedures: Mean 1.46 procedural interventions moderate
  6. Number of medications: Mean 16.6 significant polypharmacy, potential contributor to readmission
  7. Prior healthcare utilization: Most patients had 0 outpatient/emergency/inpatient visits in past year Outliers exist (up to 42 emergency visits, 76 inpatient visits) high-risk subgroup
  8. Number of diagnoses: Mean 7.4 multimorbidity; complex care needs
  9. Admission, discharge, and referral IDs: Wide categorical ranges support segmentation and pathway analysis
  10. Outliers: Extreme maximum values in LOS, visits, and labs consider capping or stratification for KPIs

Missing values

From above we noticed a significant number of records missing. Considering our dataset has 101,766 records, there are glucose serum test has 96420 (95%) and AIC result has 84748(83%) missing values. Dropping these columns could lead to significant loss of data. Instead of filling in missing lab values, glucose results were grouped into clinical risk categories and non-tested cases were analyzed separately. This allows decision-makers to understand both glycemic control and care intensity, rather than relying on imputed or misleading values.

In[14]:
glu_map = {
    'Norm': 'Normal',
    '>200': 'High',
    '>300': 'Very High'
}

a1c_map = {
    'Norm': 'Normal',
    '>7': 'Elevated',
    '>8': 'Poor Control'
}

readmission_df['glu_risk'] = readmission_df['max_glu_serum'].map(glu_map).fillna('Not Measured')
readmission_df['a1c_risk'] = readmission_df['A1Cresult'].map(a1c_map).fillna('Not Measured')

readmission_df['glu_tested'] = readmission_df['max_glu_serum'].notna().map({True: 'Yes', False: 'No'})
readmission_df['a1c_tested'] = readmission_df['A1Cresult'].notna().map({True: 'Yes', False: 'No'})

Appropriate datatypes

IDs text (categorical)
Codes categorical
Counts whole numbers
Risk / status categorical
Outcome categorical
Power BI works best when meaning number is treated as category, not numeric.

  • We didnt group all categorical columns together because they mean different things, even if they share the same datatype. Theefore the codes to change datatypes dont reflect inconsistency but clarity for later mapping for some categories.

Finalised dataset

The cleaneed dataset columns selected for anlaysis.

The final dataset was curated to retain clinically meaningful, low-noise features related to patient demographics, admission context, prior utilization, diabetes management, and readmission outcomes. High-missingness and high-cardinality variables were excluded to optimize interpretability and Power BI performance.

The following coluumns were dropped :

  1. weights - >95% missing
  2. payer_code - low relevance
  3. medical speciality - High cardinality
  4. diag 1/2/3 - increases granularity in BI
  5. Raw lab - replaced by risk flag
  6. medications - less relevance to whether diabetes med was changed or given

def validate_dataframe(df):
    print("=== DATA VALIDATION SUMMARY ===\n")
    
    for col in df.columns:
        print(f"--- Column: {col} ---")
        dtype = df[col].dtype
        missing = df[col].isna().sum()
        unique_vals = df[col].nunique()
        
        print("Type:", dtype)
        print("Missing values:", missing)
        print("Unique values:", unique_vals)
        
        # Categorical
        if pd.api.types.is_categorical_dtype(df[col]) or df[col].dtype == object:
            print("Top values:")
            print(df[col].value_counts(dropna=False).head(10))
        
        # Numeric
        elif pd.api.types.is_numeric_dtype(df[col]):
            print("Min:", df[col].min())
            print("Max:", df[col].max())
            print("Mean:", round(df[col].mean(),2))
            print("Std:", round(df[col].std(),2))
            print("Top 10 frequent values:")
            print(df[col].value_counts().head(10))
            
            # Optional: flag extreme values outside 99th percentile
            q_low = df[col].quantile(0.01)
            q_high = df[col].quantile(0.99)
            outliers = df[(df[col] < q_low) | (df[col] > q_high)]
            if not outliers.empty:
                print(f" {len(outliers)} outlier rows detected (outside 1st-99th percentile)")
        
        print("\n")

# Run validation on your dataframe
validate_dataframe(readmission_df)
